Female senior citizens outnumber males

Of the total senior citizens in the region, 54.8 percent were females while the rest
were males.

Female senior citizens outnumbered males in all age groups with the biggest gap
in the age group 80 years and over.

The percentage distribution of senior citizens decreases as age increases.
About 32.6 percent (36,255) of the population of senior citizens were 60 to 64
years old, 22.9 percent (25,457) were 65 to 69 years old and
19.7 percent (21,892) were 70 to 74 years old.

 Figure 4 presents the five ethnic groups in CAR with the most number of senior
citizens. The Ilocanos posted the highest number of senior citizens in the region
at 28.6 percent (31,854), followed by Kankanaey at 15.0 percent (16,698) and
Ibaloi/Ibaloy at 9.5 percent (10,539).
 Ilocano senior citizens were mostly in Abra, Apayao and Baguio City. A large
number of Kankanaey was located in Benguet and Mt Province. Kalinga had the
highest number belonging to the Kalinga ethnic group. Ifugao had more number
of Tuwali senior citizens.
More than half of senior citizens were household heads
 There were 352,403 household heads across the region and 19.1 percent
(67,150) were senior citizens.

Technical Notes
Household head – an adult person, male or female who is responsible for the organization
and care of the household, or who is regarded as such by the members of the household.
Household population – comprises of persons who belong to a household.
Senior citizen or elderly - refers to any resident citizen of the Philippines at least sixty (60)
years old (RA 9994).
Ethnicity - the fact or state of belonging to a social group that has a common national or
cultural tradition.
Post baccalaureate – refers to any course for which an undergraduate is required.
Post-secondary – refers to the stage of formal education following the secondary education
level covering non-degree programs that have varying duration lasting up to three years.
Proportion - a part, share, or number considered in comparative relation to a whole.
